[normal]Written evidence from
[normal] TSSA Retired Members’ Group
[normal] (TIC 03
[normal]4
[normal])
[normal]1[bold]              [bold]Introduction:[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal]              
[normal]Passenger transport is a service to people, to facilitate fulfilled lives when no other means of mobility is available.
[normal]1.2
[normal]              
[normal]Passengers do not live and work within neat administrative boundaries.
[normal]1.3
[normal]              
[normal]Services in major transport modes have to be compatible with life needs - to and from work, reaching shops, markets
[normal],
[normal] civic duties, leisure activities etc.
[normal]1.4
[normal]              
[normal]Not everyone has online facilities, or if they do 
[normal]may not
[normal] use them effectively.  
[normal]Not everyone has credit / debit facilities to make online purchases.
[normal]1.5
[normal]              
[normal]Integration of different service modes is vital to enable complex journeys.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2[bold]              [bold]TSSA[bold]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]The Transport Salaried Staffs’ Association is a recognised independent trade union, with 21,000 members in the 
[normal]UK and the Republic of Ireland[bold]; our history goes back continuously to the formation of the 
[normal]Railway Clerks’ Association[bold] in 
[normal]Sheffield
[normal] in 
[normal]1897[bold].  
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]We have 
[normal]bus industry[bold] members (
[normal]mostly in 
[normal]London
[normal], but also in the 
[normal]Irish
[normal] 
[normal]Republic
[normal], 
[normal]mostly
[normal] clerical, administrative, Control and management roles
[normal]), 
[normal]railways[bold] (
[normal]national and in both 
[normal]Irelands
[normal], in clerical, admin’, Control and management roles
[normal]), 
[normal]maritime offices[bold], 
[normal]travel trade[bold] (
[normal]agencies and some holiday suppliers
[normal]), 
[normal]railway infrastructure[bold] (
[normal]Network Rail and contractors, component suppliers
[normal]), transport-related 
[normal]call centres[bold], and transport-related 
[normal]software developers / suppliers[bold].  
[normal]2.3
[normal]              
[normal]TSSA also has members in 
[normal]Road Haulage[bold] and other transport sectors.
[normal]3[bold]              [bold]TSSA’s specialised knowledge focuses on:[bold]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]bigger picture[bold] – TSSA is a national organisation of transport workers and those people, their families and friends, their neighbours and workplace colleagues all use public transport
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]Having ‘
[normal]inside information[bold]’ on administering, organising and delivering transport
[normal]3.2.1
[normal]              
[normal]Knowing bus and train 
[normal]scheduling and operating constraints[bold], and the elements needed for service resilience
[normal]3.3
[normal]              
[normal]Knowing the deceits[bold] used to hoodwink the public and decision-makers
[normal]3.4
[normal]              
[normal]Understanding the need to have 
[normal]professional workers[bold] delivering and sustaining public passenger and freight transport
[normal]3.4.1
[normal]              
[normal]Knowing the 
[normal]dangers[bold] of using volunteers and community activists to work on a transport system on which people have a dependency.
[normal]              [bold]Statements[bold]4
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]Bigger picture[bold]’: 
[normal]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]Transport cannot be viewed in isolation; it is an enabling mechanism, or in neo-classical economics, 
[normal]derived demand[bold], 
[normal]ie
[normal] determined by other than the consumption of that utility.  Transport links
[normal] 
[normal]goods
[normal], events
[normal] and services between supplier and consumer.  While any country is divided into administrative regions and territories, its populations do not conform to those boundaries.  
[normal]4.
[normal]2
[normal]              
[normal]The inhabitants of Kings Lynn in Norfolk may have employment and leisure needs in Peterborough, Cambridgeshire rather than their own county, while the hinterland of Chester goes over the border into Wales.  Major employment centres such as Swindon have a catchment area across four other regional authorities – Wiltshire, Oxfordshire, Berkshire and Gloucestershire
[normal];
[normal] Stoke-on-Trent’s workforces come from Staffordshire and Cheshi
[normal]re;
[normal] Darlington’s regional importance serves 
[normal]the neighbouring areas of North 
[normal]Yorks
[normal], Durham and the City of Stockton.  These patterns of work and other travel crossing administrative boundaries are replicated throughout the UK.
[normal]4.
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]Car ownership is highest outside of urban centres, 
[normal]due to
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] lack of suitable passenger transport; ‘suitable’ being to reach work at times compatible with 
[normal]workplaces
[normal], travelling via routes which link home and workplace, travelling in reasonably direct routes, and fares being affordable.  
[normal]4.
[normal]4
[normal]              
[normal]Public transport provision keeps the rural carbon footprint down, 
[normal]reducing
[normal] noise pollution 
[normal]and
[normal] cutting the likelihood of accidents.  A secondary benefit is the lessened need for road maintenance with fewer vehicles using them, freeing up scarce funding authority resource for other commitments.
[normal]4.
[normal]5
[normal]              
[normal]Planning and supply of transport has to account for demand across administrative boundaries, as well as differing population densities, and timings of public transport need.  
[normal]4.[bold]6[bold]              [bold]This creates an absolute need to unify ticketing and travel passes conditions of use across boundaries.[bold]4.
[normal]7
[normal]              
[normal]The biggest anomaly is with the 
[normal]NBP[bold] - National Bus Pass – issued to all 
[normal]who age-qualify 
[normal]but 
[normal]often (‘
[normal]rurally
[normal]’) 
[normal]no, few or unsuitable services to use.  This is not an argument against the NBP. 
[normal]4.
[normal]8
[normal]              
[normal]Some bus operators are dependent upon the revenue from National Bus Passes to stay viable.  Bus operator Trent Barton in Nottinghamshire claims that NBP generates 25% of their revenue (
[normal]statement to National Pensioners’ Convention Transport Working Party, August 2013
[normal]), and without that income, the company would not be viable.  NBP users spend money in their destinations, bringing a wider benefit to the economy.  Some of that money would be spent anyway, but supplementary spend, on refreshment and other leisure, puts extra money into circulation.  While in the major centres, mobility is effectively taken for granted, and the circulation of money on the broader regional economy is a given, this is less so in thinner-densities of population.
[normal]4.[bold]9[bold]              [bold]This is an argument for suitable and sufficient public passenger transport, with unified terms and conditions between neighbouring issuing authorities.[bold]5
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]Inside information[bold]’: 
[normal]5
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]TSSA’s unique combination of roles and grades throughout the transport industries gives us access to planning principles, operating criteria, service management and assessment of efficacy.  
[normal]5
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]The principle of passenger transport planning, when I joined most of 
[normal]my industries
[normal], was to consider the passenger first, to build service
[normal]s
[normal] and route structure
[normal]s
[normal] around their needs.  This 
[normal]ended
[normal] as transport 
[normal]became
[normal] private, where service was determined by financial reward and appropriate local, regional or national authorities had to finance any shortfall arising from this mutation.  
[normal]5
[normal].3
[normal]              
[normal]Transport is rarely purely urban, nor purely ‘rural’ – the best means of utilising transport vehicles (
[normal]road or rail
[normal]) is to integrate schedules, making best use of buses and trains.  Types of service and ways to link locations may vary for time of day and day of week – the difference between compelled travel and discretionary travel.  That definition gap often blurs – is someone travelling to pay a Council Tax bill once a month at the Town Hall, a discretionary or compelled journey?
[normal]5
[normal].4
[normal]              
[normal]Passengers having to cross administrative boundaries often found their bus services in particular redu
[normal]cing in frequency (
[normal]from, for example, daily to market days at the regional centre determined by the bus operator, not necessarily the centre used by the community
[normal]), capacity (
[normal]double-deck buses replaced by single-deck vehicles
[normal]), and service (
[normal]going from hourly or better on days operated to just one or two buses per day
[normal]).
[normal]  
[normal]5
[normal].5
[normal]              
[normal]Lack of a commercial traffic from a Hertfordshire village, 
[normal]Sarratt[bold], just outside Watford, resulted in the hourly daily except Sunday double-deck route 318 bus service provided by London Transport (
[normal]which handed over ‘country area’ operation
[normal]s
[normal] to the National Bus Company in 1970
[normal]) steadily 
[normal]reducing
[normal] in all aspects – trips per day, days of operation
[normal],
[normal] replacement by smaller and single-deck 
[normal]buses
[normal] until toward the end of the 20th century, the village had lost all of its scheduled services and became reliant on a community facility staffed by volunteers.  That service had 
[normal]imperfect
[normal] operation
[normal]al
[normal] 
[normal]certainty
[normal] as drive
[normal]r
[normal] volunteers could not be guaranteed for all the 
[normal]scheduled
[normal] trips.
[normal]5
[normal].6
[normal]              
[normal]Computer scheduling has allowed ‘integrated schedules’ to a far greater degree than manual compilation which preceded it.  More sophisticated systems allowed efficient linking up of different routes’ journeys.  Simpler ‘hub and spoke’ route patterns have been transformed, especially outside of major cities, into integrated operating patterns
[normal]5
[normal].6.1
[normal]              
[normal]Eg
[normal] - a bus travelling route ‘A’ from a centre to an outlying point, then to form the next trip on route ‘B’ to a different location, then to a route ‘C’ which might serve yet more places.  Other vehicles on those routes could be drawn from different routes, which would be invisible to users except when a double- or single-deck bus appeared for no visible reason instead of the usual type.  
[normal]5
[normal].7
[normal]              
[normal]When a capacity increase occurred, no-one was inconvenienced, but where a scheduling efficiency reduce
[normal]d
[normal] carrying capacity (
[normal]link
[normal]ing
[normal] two other operations
[normal],
[normal] bringing a single-deck vehicle 
[normal]vice
[normal] a previously-operated double-decker
[normal]), people could be left behind, 
[normal]possibly
[normal] with no later bus to catch.  This leaves funding authorities with a dilemma – ensuring by subsidy that a route is of sufficient capacity might mean paying excessively, as either scheduling efficiencies would be lost (
[normal]raising operating costs
[normal]) or paying for a double-decker to cover irrelevant workings on an integrated operating roster, 
[normal]giving
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] bus operator money for nothing.  
[normal]5
[normal].8
[normal]              
[normal]The same applies for rail 
[normal]beyond
[normal] major centres – 
[normal]TOC[bold] (Train Operating Company) franchises determine service (
[normal]timings, frequencies and capacity
[normal]) but do not impose requirements to serve the community beyond the rail station.  Trains will run from very early to very late, often seven days a week, but buses may not.  Invariably 
[normal]a
[normal] bus operator is called upon to fill in the gap, which 
[normal]may create
[normal] a 
[normal]subsidy
[normal] burden for the authorities, 
[normal]reflected i
[normal]n ‘opportunity cost’ 
[normal]of
[normal] the 
[normal]diverted 
[normal]resource.
[normal]5
[normal].9
[normal]              
[normal]Outside major centres, less-dense populations and the spread of routes from transport interchange points creates inefficient bus use and poor interchange between modes.  ‘Rural’ populations always take a bigger hit on service quality than urban dwellers who have strength in numbers to determine bus service standards.  
[normal]5[bold].10[bold]              [bold]A[bold] national service obligation pattern and code of conduct is essential to link transport modes and [bold]sustain[bold] the skeins of a caring Society.[bold]5
[normal].11
[normal]              
[normal]A
[normal] classic 
[normal]apocryphal[bold] example of bus industry obfuscation was 
[normal]reputedly[bold] 
[normal]([bold]former[bold]) route 265 between Sheffield and Chesterfield[bold], 
[normal]serving
[normal] South Yorkshire and Derbyshire
[normal],
[normal] for which evidence cannot 
[normal]be obtained as the information i
[normal]s ‘commercially
[normal] confidential’
[normal].  It was widely 
[normal]‘known’[bold], again 
[normal]without evidence[bold] that 
[normal]the operator
[normal] had subsidy from both authorities to provide a 
[normal]frequent
[normal] daily operation along 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]seemingly[bold] viable 
[normal]route 
[normal]without subsidy
[normal].  These 
[normal]rumours persisted[bold] until the route was re-numbered.
[normal]  It was impossible to confirm/refute, and public money vanished unaccountably.
[normal]5
[normal].12
[normal]              
[normal]In the 
[normal]west country[bold], buses always ran late along one urban corridor, highlighted in a 
[normal]BBC Radio Four programme,[bold] File on Four[bold], on Tuesday 09 August 2005; BBC researchers and presenter(s) lacked inside knowledge to 
[normal]see
[normal] what was really going on, nor to see how the local authority had been duped into premature and un-necessary spend on road improvements.  No matter what the Local Authority was persuaded to do, and did, buses continually ran late, even with bus priority measures.  
[normal]I have the programme’s transcript.[bold]  
[normal]File on Four
[normal] is a recorded programme and did not have an imminent editorial deadline to meet.  
[normal]5
[normal].12.1
[normal]              
[normal]The truth was simpler: the bus operator was running the service with one vehicle LESS than the service frequency and RTRT - 
[normal]round trip running time[bold] - demanded.  The maximum number of buses a route requires is called the PVR – 
[normal]Peak Vehicle Requirement[bold] –
[normal] determined from the time taken at the busiest period for a single vehicle to start from its origin point, ready to pick up its first passengers, reach its destination and alight all its passengers, take a ‘
[normal]turnround
[normal] time’ break and make the return service journey and be ready 
[normal]for
[normal] its next journey.  Dividing the RTRT by the 
[normal]headway[bold] (
[normal]frequency of service to be provided
[normal]) gives the number of vehicles required.  Thus a 40 minute RTRT and a 10 minute headway requires FOUR buses; a sixty seven minute RTRT on a five minute headway requires 13.4 buses…  ‘Point four’ of a bus is impossible, therefore fourteen vehicles are needed to run the route, by extending the standing time at one or both ends of the route.  
[normal]5
[normal].12.2
[normal]              
[normal]However, if a bus operator cannot or will not provide the missing ‘point six’, the route m
[normal]ight
[normal] still run with thirteen buses, despite submitting a full schedule to the Traffic Commissioners and/or Local Authority.  The service runs 
[normal]increasingly 
[normal]late as the 
[normal]day progresses; the 
[normal]operator 
[normal]has to
[normal] cancel at least one round trip later to avoid paying drivers overtime rates for late running.  
[normal]5
[normal].12.3
[normal]              
[normal] ‘Inside information’ would have told the BBC this – it 
[normal]opted
[normal] not to question, not to ask for an external verification of the operator’s claims and to broadcast material as it was given.  The lack of inside information, the skills and knowledge of transport workers, will continue to allow distortion of facts, and keep false impressions vibrant.  
[normal]Transport operators deliberately suppress knowledge[bold].
[normal]5
[normal].13
[normal]              
[normal]This accepted level of deceit has to change; we have to re-impose principles of planning for passengers first.  We have to recognise and act on the ‘bigger picture’, to integrate people and Society.  This also means that the technical skills used to plan, deliver and administer transport must become more transparent and more accountable.
[normal]5[bold].14[bold]              [bold]Laws covering Companies, taxation, finance, and the guidelines on accountancy practice must change to show where and how public money is being used, not just in transport.[bold]6
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]Scheduling and operating constraints[bold]’: 
[normal]6
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]An operator only has so many buses and trains.  On the railways, train operations are determined by the franchise; on the roads, vehicles are numbered by the likelihood of a profit from fares along the route network or subsidy from a relevant authority.  In both cases, scheduling efficiency determines advantageous uses of equipment.  In both modern cases, the transport supplier’s operating desires come ahead of passengers’ needs.
[normal]6
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]In major centres, bus route patterns and service 
[normal]levels
[normal] 
[normal]may be
[normal] determined (
[normal]London in particular, Newcastle is set to follow
[normal]) by a route contracts regime.  Beyond these centres, bus operators since national ‘deregulation’ (
[normal]except London
[normal]) in 1986
[normal] may operate where and when they wish
[normal].  
[normal]Before
[normal] 1986, regional Traffic Commissioners control bus service
[normal] level
[normal]s.  The emphasis switched from serving a passenger need to operating only 
[normal]where
[normal] positive net revenue
[normal]s might be found
[normal].
[normal]6
[normal].3
[normal]              
[normal]An operation 
[normal]can be
[normal] schedule
[normal]d
[normal] so that 
[normal]for 
[normal]any subsidised se
[normal]gment
[normal], the paying authority 
[normal]is under-writing
[normal] an extra vehicle on that route 
[normal]by a
[normal] sole operator.  Service planners work for an employer, not passengers, apart from remaining municipal bus operators.  This gives the bus company an opportunity for a new bus for nothing or very little, as the funding authority will 
[normal]end up
[normal] paying for crewing the extra vehicle – a bus on the road for most of a ‘traffic day’ (
[normal]early
[normal] 
[normal]morning to evening Monday-Friday
[normal],
[normal] possibly plus earlier/later services for commuting workers
[normal]) requires two drivers.  Limitation of work hours (
[normal]on the road
[normal]) prohibit a single driver from working throughout.  An operator may ‘discover’ a new (
[normal]or nearly-new
[normal]) bus available at little or no extra cost, to also be used elsewhere, outside of the ‘PVR’ (
[normal]above
[normal]) 
[normal]and at weekends, 
[normal]on other revenue-earning operations.
[normal]6
[normal].4
[normal]              
[normal]The paying authority’s other choice is 
[normal]open
[normal] the missing journeys to tender.  It will then be paying a third party to inefficiently use a bus to fill those gaps.  ‘Missing journeys’ tend not to occur in urban settings, placing extra financial burdens on outlying funding authorities.  This is an excess cost in either scenario, and lacking skills to decode this will always mean those paying authorities 
[normal]may line
[normal] the pockets of unscrupulous operators.  
[normal]6[bold].5[bold]              [bold]Local Authorities subsidis[bold]ing bus routes and under-writing rail[bold] services must [bold]have[bold] ring-fenced transport ‘professionals’ to analyse their passenger operation subsidy to suppliers.[bold]6
[normal].6
[normal]              
[normal]One 
[normal]urban 
[normal]example of an over-generous schedule was a
[normal]n
[normal] East London trunk route, which on the successful TfL tender required ‘X’ vehicles.  Investigations later revealed that the route was 
[normal]run
[normal] with ‘X-minus-1’ buses.  The route at one end terminated inside its home garage; as a 
[normal]given
[normal] bus arrived ex-passenger service, it would be left ready for the next departure, having been fully fuelled at the start of the day.  Garage staff removed the arriving ‘running number’ (
[normal]the identity of that day’s combination of trips
[normal]) and installed the next available number in the route sequence.  On paper, this was the full ‘X’ allocation of buses; the turn-round time inside the garage hid the identity swap and enabled the true ‘X-minus-1’ operation.  
[normal]6.6.1
[normal]              
[normal]In London the density of population and generous location of intelligent eyes uncovered this, but in outlying areas, where fewer people 
[normal]exist
[normal] to detect this, public purse costs will accumulate.  
[normal]6
[normal].7
[normal]              
[normal]A major issue with rural bus operations is 
[normal]bus[bold] standardisation[bold]; European Union rule
[normal]s
[normal] govern width and length maxima, which most manufacturers adopt as default, charging extra for variations.  The EU-wide maximum permitted width of passenger service vehicles is 2m55, but this is often excessive for country lanes and narrow roads in ‘traditional’ centres.  This leave
[normal]s
[normal] undesirable options
[normal]:
[normal](1) purchase 
[normal]dearer, 
[normal]non-standard (
[normal]ie
[normal] narrower
[normal]) vehicles, which may reduce carrying capacity;
[normal](2) schedule less efficiently so that buses do not pass each other in restricted areas;
[normal](3) use minibuses, which have limited capacity, and may not satisfy travel demand.
[normal]6[bold].8[bold]              [bold]Suppliers of buses to the UK must offer reasonably priced and availab[bold]le[bold] smaller vehicles of suitable and sufficient capacity.  This may mean centralised manufacturing support, either to bus builders or operators or to Local Authorities procuring routes and services.[bold]6
[normal].9
[normal]              
[normal]Rural rail operations are constrained by two key factors – trains which are too small (
[normal]particularly ‘Class 15x’ typ
[normal]es of trains – series 150, 
[normal]156, 158 notably
[normal]) and single-tracked 
[normal]route 
[normal]sections.  The former restriction leads to dangerous overcrowding –
[normal] 
[normal]eg
[normal] the route linking Birmingham 
[normal]and
[normal] Norwich, where two-carriage class 158 trains are used, with excessive standing and crush-loading over segments 
[normal]serving
[normal] bigger intermediate and terminal locations.  The latter restriction prevents a ‘clock-face’ service from being operated (
[normal]ie
[normal] so many minutes past each hour
[normal]), as ‘passing loops’ act as hindrances to increased or regular operations.  
[normal]6[bold].10[bold]              [bold]Train[bold] supply must be increased – [bold]type 15x rolling stock is not yet life-expired, and should be rebuilt [bold]as[bold] longer trains, re-engineering single-carriage (or ‘car’) units into two-car trains, and 2-car trains into three-car formations.  By re-forming those trains, new rolling stock would be [bold]needed[bold] to maintain and improve services.  This would be a[bold]n[bold] opportunity for UK train manufacturing and component suppliers, and would help to meet increasing passenger demand, as well as developing a better service for rural and less-densely-populated areas.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6[bold].11[bold]              [bold]Railway track patterns must be analysed for the restrictions they[bold] impose[bold]; double-tracking and use of former routes needs attention; where track doubling cannot be achieved, opportunities for more ‘passing loops’ should be examined.[bold]6
[normal].12
[normal]              
[normal]Extreme loadings on small trains often arise from poor or nil alternative – a bus may run parallel or close for some or all of those segments, but the elapsed time on the roads and possibly infrequency of operation deters these options, and ‘forces’ those who must use public transport on to trains, or if they are capable, to use private cars.
[normal]6[bold].13[bold]              [bold]An inspection regime [bold]should[bold] be instituted, ring-fence resourced and sustained, to audit and examine claims [bold]from[bold] operators of road and rail passenger services; this regime must be staffed by professional transport people.  Scheduling constraints must be described and demonstrated by bus operators in receipt of public funds.  The practice of claiming commercial confidentiality in the use of public funds [bold]must[bold] be rescinded; where public money is used, those receiving it must show how, where and when this resource is utilised.[bold]7
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]Knowing the deceits[bold]’: 
[normal]7
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]ATOC[bold] (Association of Train Operating Companies) is dependent on no-one questioning it.  In 
[normal]December 2011[bold], ATOC released a ‘breakdown’ of how each penny per £ of the rail fare was divided up.  This was a technical deceit, too complex for media to challenge – it went beyond the time-slot a radio or 
[normal]tv
[normal] programme could allocate, and would not productively fill column inches of printed media.  I asked ATOC if I could speak to the analysis compiler; the instant reply was ‘he’s left the industry’.  I asked for a means to contact him; the instant reply was ‘we have no means to reach him’.  My enquiry was 
[normal]two 
[normal]days 
[normal]after
[normal] the 
[normal]press release
[normal].
[normal]7
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]A typical ATOC deceit in this analysis was that N% of each fare went in staff costs; so, imagine two passengers are in the queue at Waterloo ticket office…  The first passenger asks for a day return 
[normal]to Surbiton (
[normal]a London south western suburb, served by local trains
[normal]), which for the sake of argument costs £6, out of which N% 
[normal]is for
[normal] staff overheads.  The second passenger wants an open First Class return to Exeter, which for the sake of argument costs £200.  The booking clerk will only have pressed a different combination of computer buttons.  Is the same N% really applicable for both transactions?  ATOC
[normal]’s
[normal] analysis 
[normal]ignored
[normal] internet bookings, companies such as 
[normal]Trainline[bold], 
[normal]and
[normal] purchases from a station ticket vending machine [TVM].  Assuming a TVM is
[normal] 
[normal]working
[normal] (and both passengers understand how to use 
[normal]it,
[normal] and are able to)
[normal], each passenger has only pressed different buttons on the same machine.  Both transactions 
[normal]take
[normal] the same time and resource, both cost the same for the
[normal] train operator to deliver.  I
[normal]s the argument that staff overheads are averaged per transaction?  If so, over which period, and what is the basis of the calculation by ATOC, given that each TOC pays different wages to their staff, has different 
[normal](
[normal]Commercially Confidential!
[normal]) 
[normal]contracts for their ticket machines, and pays different rentals to the freeholder, Network Rail?  ATOC is also very good at selectively deriving misleading positive data from quarterly 
[normal]Passenger Focus[bold] satisfaction reports.
[normal]7[bold].3[bold]              [bold]Proofs of[bold] claims of constraints [bold]are[bold] essential if the UK is to fairly cost the provision of transport services across the country.  Again, the need to change the rules of train franchises, the laws on Companies, Finance and Tax, the guidelines on accountancy practice [bold]is[bold] [bold]vital[bold].[bold]7
[normal].4
[normal]              
[normal]Change 
[normal]is 
[normal]needed in recording deduction of service charges 
[normal]on
[normal] operators 
[normal]published
[normal] accounts
[normal]; these are
[normal] paid to external providers (
[normal]usually a parent company’s subsidiary 
[normal]for
[normal] centralised HR, IT, payroll, uniform etc
[normal]), taken from the profit and loss statement.  These inflated ‘service charges’ are consolidated on Corporate accounts making it impossible to see how this money is disbursed.  
[normal]7
[normal].5
[normal]              
[normal]External cash flows from the subsidiary reduce operating profit and tax liability without harming the company’s viability.  UK train franchise rules limit profit margins to 3%, but ‘profit’ is whatever 
[normal]an
[normal] accountant determines, as long as accountancy guidelines permit that latitude.
[normal]7
[normal].6
[normal]              
[normal]The other un
[normal]addressed 
[normal]issue 
[normal]in public accounting of transport companies is that 
[normal]‘
[normal]profit
[normal]’
[normal] is deceitful – the 
[normal]key
[normal] value is ‘return on capital’.  Profit only arises from the day-to-day running of the operation; return on capital, which is unconstrained by neither law nor contracts, is what the operator takes back for its investment.  The 
[normal]Financial Times
[normal] has pointed out that in the transport sector, ‘return on capital’ is effectively a licence to print money, and makes ‘profit’ irrelevant.  
[normal]“In some cases you can make between 50 per cent and 70 per cent return on capital employed”[bold] said Mark 
[normal]Manduca
[normal], Bank of America Merrill Lynch transport analyst in London, but 
[normal]“profit margins are low – typically in single digits...  Franchising does not require train operators to tie up large amounts of capital, which can ensure strong returns”[bold] (
[normal]Financial Times
[normal], WED02JAN13).
[normal]  
[normal]8
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]Professional workers[bold]’: 
[normal]8
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]Trained and competent staff are the backbone of any transport operation, especially where the internet is not suitable to determine a means to travel.  
[normal]8
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]Machines do not answer questions; 
[normal]TVMs[bold] display highest fares first, imposing a silent, un-notified duty to interrogate the machine for alternatives.  In the case of 
[normal]South West Trains at Waterloo[bold], all requests to a TVM for a journey to Basingstoke will first offer the routeing via Reading which is infrequent, longer than the through service would take and requires a change of trains via non-adjacent platforms.  This ticket is also valid for the cheaper, direct services, which run up to four times each hour and will take up to an hour less than the ‘via Reading’ option.  It is not possible to see from this enquiry at a machine that this is a less-desirable option, let alone why.
[normal]8
[normal].3
[normal]              
[normal]Abellio[bold] Greater Anglia TVMs within Greater London[bold] do not offer holders of the London ‘Freedom Pass’ the opportunity to buy a ticket onward from the ‘Zone 6’ boundary – this leaves the passenger with the option of queuing at the booking office window or paying twice for that segment of the trip.  This facility is available on the 
[normal]Southern[bold] franchise, so it can be done.
[normal]8
[normal].4
[normal]              
[normal]There is no requirement for TVMs to be consistent in the facilities offered, nor for them to have the same layout, all of which forms a disincentive to use.
[normal]8[bold].5[bold]              [bold]TVMs must offer [bold]services[bold] consistent[bold]ly[bold], openly showing how to access best value ticket[bold]s[bold] and the same term[bold]inologie[bold]s used [bold]across[bold] UK railway[bold]s[bold].  This would best be served [bold]by a national ownership, whose single management structure could enforce this.[bold]8
[normal].6
[normal]              
[normal]Thi
[normal]s extort
[normal]ion
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] replicated across the UK, regardless of TOC
[normal] 
[normal]or location.  At unstaffed ‘rural’ stations, or outer suburban stations where there is no continuous staffing, the only means of legitimate travel is a ticket from the 
[normal]TVM, assuming it is working
[normal] a
[normal]nd
[normal] the passenger 
[normal]can
[normal] use it.  Longer journeys (
[normal]those
[normal] across franchise boundar
[normal]ies
[normal]) cannot be bought from most 
[normal]TVMs
[normal].  
[normal]8
[normal].7
[normal]              
[normal]Despite the size and programming capacity of TVMs, TOCs rarely put the national fares network
[normal] into them
[normal].  However, revenue 
[normal]staff
[normal] on trains (
[normal]guards or travelling ticket inspectors
[normal]) 
[normal]have
[normal] portable 
[normal]machines which have
[normal] 
[normal]all
[normal] national fares
[normal],
[normal] so TOCs 
[normal]can
[normal] put this facility on their 
[normal]TVMs.
