[normal].9
[normal]              
[normal]Professional workers 
[normal]oversee
[normal] 
[normal]transport 
[normal]schedules.  The more a computer 
[normal]does
[normal], less individual skill is needed 
[normal]for
[normal] corporate outputs.  This reduces operation
[normal]al
[normal] 
[normal]sustainability
[normal], de-skilling those who would be tasked with recovering a degraded situation.  In urban regions, the availability of vehicles and
[normal] people may bring about a fast
[normal] resolution, but degraded ‘rural’
[normal] 
[normal]service is critical to livelihoods and safety.  Resource is sparser
[normal];
[normal] reliance on professional Control
[normal]lers
[normal] to understand and react is 
[normal]vit
[normal]al.  
[normal]8
[normal].10
[normal]              
[normal]My year on the 
[normal]Underground’s ‘Graffiti Task Force’[bold] 
[normal]revealed
[normal] 
[normal]that s
[normal]ocial issues transcend transport
[normal] 
[normal]– there is no definable boundary.  Keeping ‘transport’ separate from ‘Society’ is self-defeating.  Those who know that only technology stands between them and committing an anti-social event are aware that the chances of successful escape rise exponentially.  To catch unwanted behaviour
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]echnology has to be 
[normal]working
[normal], accurate
[normal] and
[normal] monitored; someone has to become aware that something untoward is happening.  The critical issue, we discovered on the Underground is ‘reaction time’ – how fast can an adverse incident be recognised and resource arrive at the scene?  
[normal]8
[normal].11
[normal]              
[normal]Rural distances compound issues, risking 
[normal]more
[normal] deterioration before resource arrive
[normal]s
[normal]; 
[normal]Network Rail[bold] some years ago cut their 
[normal]Mobile Operations Managers[bold] (MOMs) locations.  In 
[normal]Wessex[bold] region, MOMs serving Weymouth (Dorset) 
[normal]were based at
[normal] Eastleigh (Hampshire), 
[normal]over
[normal] seventy miles
[normal] away. 
[normal] If 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]railway
[normal] incident 
[normal]needed
[normal] attention
[normal], t
[normal]he only 
[normal]fast 
[normal]means of 
[normal]getting
[normal] 
[normal]west of
[normal] Poole was rail, the means most likely disrupted.  Professional worke
[normal]rs are more effective than a phone, radio or a CCTV unit
[normal].
[normal]8
[normal].12
[normal]              
[normal]The UK has no shortage of people willing to become transport professionals – the reluctance is in the employers who service the corporate need first.  A cultural and commercial shift is essential to improve the transport quality in all areas, not just the lesser-populated regions.
[normal]8[bold].13[bold]              [bold]A railway needs operating and maintenance staff within reasonable distances, suitably and sufficiently equipped to travel and work on the ‘permanent way’.  A risk analysis may show low likelihood of an event but the other aspect, the severity indicator has been ignored.  A railway is a safety-critical facility: lives cannot be reduced to half of a risk analysis.[bold]9
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]Dangers[bold]’: 
[normal]9
[normal].1
[normal]              
[normal]Community 
[normal]railway
[normal] experiments 
[normal]exist
[normal] with volunteers 
[normal]at
[normal] stations
[normal].
[normal]  While this 
[normal]gives
[normal] human presence, training cannot cover all 
[normal]outcomes
[normal].  Risk Assessment matrices rank adverse event likelihood against impact.  Volunteers in safety critical environment
[normal]s
[normal] may 
[normal]not
[normal] 
[normal]know
[normal] the worst a railway can deliver, but are unlikely to 
[normal]safely
[normal] manage such events, and may even 
[normal]worsen them
[normal].  
[normal]9
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]Volunteers must be competent to the same standard 
[normal]as paid staff
[normal].  A volunteer 
[normal]alone in
[normal] an otherwise unstaffed station is 
[normal]equally 
[normal]at risk in the dull period as 
[normal]in
[normal] peak hours.  Station duties are a mix of clerical, routine and critical; to sub-divide these aspects is to 
[normal]raise the risk profile
[normal].  
[normal]9
[normal].3
[normal]              
[normal]Volunteers (
[normal]from bitter experience 
[normal]elsewhere
[normal]) are most likely to 
[normal]be absent
[normal] in adverse weather, to take time off at short notice leaving no cover, to take short-cuts because no-one is looking and 
[normal]rarely
[normal] 
[normal]see
[normal] actual
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]only
[normal] perceived risk.  The 
[normal]first rule of the railway[bold] is ‘everything affects everything else’; that was 
[normal]my
[normal] first lesson when I joined the main line railway in 2000.
[normal]9
[normal].4
[normal]              
[normal]Volunteers may be 
[normal]useful
[normal] 
[normal]to keep
[normal] quieter railway
[normal]s viable
[normal], but mercenary interpretation by the TOC
[normal] determines that
[normal].  Paid staff contribute to the local economy, increasing money circulation; volunteers have just an uplift (
[normal]valuable but not the same
[normal]).
